'''Haji Gokool Meah''' (–) was an industrialist and philanthropist. He was born in , in what was then . He was originally named '''Modhoo'''. His father died shortly before his birth and his mother remarried. 
As a small child, his family left Kashmir and ended up in  where in  they signed up as  bound for the  fields of . On ,  they arrived in Trinidad aboard the ''''. They were indentured at the  in . After three months, his mother died of  and his stepfather took little interest in him. He was informally adopted by a  couple who gave him the name Gokool. 
Once he was old enough, Gokool secured his own indentureship contract with the Concord Estate. He renewed his contract once it expired, and then went out on his own. He purchased a  cart and made a living hauling sugar cane to the factory at , then the second largest  in the world. After a few years of this trade, he sold his cart and established a shop in  on the road to  (now part of the   at Pointe-à-Pierre). 
He married Rojan and had 17 children, 11 of whom survived. From shopkeeping he moved on to  cultivation, establishing one of the early cocoa s in the  valley. From cocoa he moved on the , becoming one of the major landlords in . He also established himself as a  magnate, establishing the Metro cinema in collaboration with . He later split with them and renamed his cinema the Globe Cinema, eventually operating a string of five cinemas in Port of Spain and San Fernando.
In  he performed the  (Muslim pilgrimage to ). In his will, he established the Haji Gokool Meah Trust, a trust to continue the charitable works which had earned him the title ''Meah'' (benefactor).